channel.title: Bogong High Plains
channel.description: The Bogong High Plains are part of the Alpine National Park. Includes Bogong Village, Falls Creek, Mt Nelse, Mt Cope, Mt Bogong, Mt Fainter, Mt McKay, Pretty Valley, & Buckety Plains.

item.title: Euphrasia crassiuscula subsp. glandulifera
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Most plants of this subspecies had finished flowering st this time. This was the only plant found with reasonable flowers remaining. This grows alongside subsp. eglandulosa which was in the peak of its flowering time.

item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Occurs here with sp. aff. robusta (NW Alps) which has hairy leaves (looks greyish, especially on upper stem), more yellow flowers and, at this location, longer ligules.

item.title: Podolepis sp. aff. robusta (N.E. Alps)
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: At this location it occurs with P. robusta which has glabrous leaves, more orangey flowers and shorter ligules.

item.title: Stylidium montanum
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: One small patch of plants at the low point of a saddle (probably where water gathers) on track to Mt Nelse. S. armeria armeria occasionally on either side. Short leaves and rhizomatous clumping (2nd pic) are key features for S. montanum.

item.title: Craspedia alba
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Just this single population known in Victoria. Grows in only a dozen or so moist depressions in this alpine herbfield on black peaty mud. The depressions (see final pic) that contain C. alba are generally about 2-3m x 4m. All plants had finished flowering and gone to seed except for this one and a couple more that had past their best.

item.title: Acrothamnus montanus
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: All shrubs in this windswept alpine heathland reach a height of about 50cm. Could be A. hookeri but predominantly flat leaves indicates A. montanus.
